  ™Å             A      s ¸  8…      8…      ™È      8…      8…                                      8…      8…      8…      %v     %v                                     ™È                                      8…      8…      8…      ¿x     8…      8…      8…      8…              ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ            ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ˇˇˇˇ    ™Å     8…      8…      8…      8…      8…      8…                                                              8…      8…      8…      ˛  	    :     	                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      Big dataFrom Wikipedia, the free encyclopediaThis article is about large collections of data. For the band, see† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_Data_(band)" \o "Big Data (band)" Big Data (band).Big data HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-1" [1] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-2" [2]†is the term for a collection of† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_set" \o "Data set" data sets†so large and complex that it becomes difficult to process using on-hand database management tools or traditional data processing applications. The challenges include capture, curation, storage, HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-3" [3]†search, sharing, transfer, analysis HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-4" [4]†and visualization. The trend to larger data sets is due to the additional information derivable from analysis of a single large set of related data, as compared to separate smaller sets with the same total amount of data, allowing correlations to be found to "spot business trends, determine quality of research, prevent diseases,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legal_citation_analysis" \o "Legal citation analysis" link legal citations, combat crime, and determine real-time roadway traffic conditions." HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-Economist-5" [5] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-BD-HB-R-01-6" [6] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-BD-HB-R-02-7" [7] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Viegas-UserActivityonWikipedia.gif"  INCLUDEPICTURE "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Viegas-UserActivityonWikipedia.gif/220px-Viegas-UserActivityonWikipedia.gif" \* MERGEFORMATINET  HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Viegas-UserActivityonWikipedia.gif" \o "Enlarge"  INCLUDEPICTURE "http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.24wmf1/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" \* MERGEFORMATINET A visualization created by IBM of Wikipedia edits. At multiple† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terabyte" \o "Terabyte" terabytes†in size, the text and images of Wikipedia are a classic example of big data. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hilbert_InfoGrowth.png"  INCLUDEPICTURE "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7c/Hilbert_InfoGrowth.png/220px-Hilbert_InfoGrowth.png" \* MERGEFORMATINET  HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Hilbert_InfoGrowth.png" \o "Enlarge"  INCLUDEPICTURE "http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.24wmf1/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" \* MERGEFORMATINET Growth of and Digitization of Global Information Storage Capacity; source: HYPERLINK "http://www.martinhilbert.net/WorldInfoCapacity.html" http://www.martinhilbert.net/WorldInfoCapacity.htmlAs of 2012, limits on the size of data sets that are feasible to process in a reasonable amount of time were on the order of† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exabyte" \o "Exabyte" exabytes†of data, that is, millions of† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terabyte" \o "Terabyte" terabytes. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-Ars_Technica-8" [8]†Scientists regularly encounter limitations due to large data sets in many areas, including† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meteorology" \o "Meteorology" meteorology, HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genomics" \o "Genomics" genomics, HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-9" [9]† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connectomics" \o "Connectomics" connectomics, complex physics simulations, HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-10" [10]†and biological and environmental research. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-11" [11]†The limitations also affect HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_search_engine" \o "Web search engine" Internet search,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finance" \o "Finance" finance†and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business_informatics" \o "Business informatics" business informatics. Data sets grow in size in part because they are increasingly being gathered by ubiquitous information-sensing mobile devices, aerial sensory technologies ( HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Remote_sensing" \o "Remote sensing" remote sensing), software logs, cameras, microphones,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radio-frequency_identification" \o "Radio-frequency identification" radio-frequency identification†readers, and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wireless_sensor_networks" \o "Wireless sensor networks" wireless sensor networks. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-12" [12] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-13" [13] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-14" [14]†The world's technological per-capita capacity to store information has roughly doubled every 40 months since the 1980s; HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-HilbertLopez2011-15" [15]†as of 2012, every day 2.5† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exabyte" \o "Exabyte" exabytes†(2.5◊1018) of data were created. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-16" [16]†The challenge for large enterprises is determining who should own big data initiatives that straddle the entire organization. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-17" [17]Big data is difficult to work with using most† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relational_database_management_system" \o "Relational database management system" relational database management systems†and desktop statistics and visualization packages, requiring instead "massively parallel software running on tens, hundreds, or even thousands of servers". HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-18" [18]†What is considered "big data" varies depending on the capabilities of the organization managing the set, and on the capabilities of the applications that are traditionally used to process and analyze the data set in its domain. "For some organizations, facing hundreds of gigabytes of data for the first time may trigger a need to reconsider data management options. For others, it may take tens or hundreds of terabytes before data size becomes a significant consideration." HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-19" [19]Contents 8.4†Society[116] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "See_also" 9†See also HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "References" 10†References HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "External_links" 11†External links HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "Further_reading" 12†Further readingDefinition[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=1" \o "Edit section: Definition" edit]Big Data usually includes data sets with sizes beyond the ability of commonly used software tools to† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_acquisition" \o "Data acquisition" capture,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_curation" \o "Data curation" curate, manage, and process the data within a tolerable elapsed time. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-Editorial-20" [20]†Big data sizes are a constantly moving target, as of 2012†ranging from a few dozen terabytes to many† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petabyte" \o "Petabyte" petabytes†of data in a single data set.In a 2001 research report HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-21" [21]†and related lectures,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/META_Group" \o "META Group" META Group†(now† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gartner" \o "Gartner" Gartner) analyst Doug Laney defined data growth challenges and opportunities as being three-dimensional, i.e. increasing volume (amount of data), velocity (speed of data in and out), and variety (range of data types and sources). Gartner, and now much of the industry, continue to use this "3Vs" model for describing big data. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-22" [22]†In 2012,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gartner" \o "Gartner" Gartner†updated its definition as follows: "Big data is high volume, high velocity, and/or high variety information assets that require new forms of processing to enable enhanced decision making, insight discovery and process optimization." HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-23" [23]†Additionally, a new V "Veracity" is added by some organizations to describe it. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-24" [24]If Gartnerís definition (the 3Vs) is still widely used, the growing maturity of the concept fosters a more sound difference between big data and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Business_Intelligence" \o "Business Intelligence" Business Intelligence, regarding data and their use:Business Intelligence uses† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Descriptive_statistics" \o "Descriptive statistics" descriptive statistics†with data with high information density to measure things, detect trends etc.;Big data uses† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inductive_statistics" \o "Inductive statistics" inductive statistics†and concepts from† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nonlinear_system_identification" \o "Nonlinear system identification" nonlinear system identification† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-SAB1-25" [25]†to infer laws (regressions, nonlinear relationships, and causal effects) from large data sets† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-26" [26]†to reveal relationships, dependencies and perform predictions of outcomes and behaviors. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-SAB1-25" [25] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-27" [27]Big science[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=2" \o "Edit section: Big science" edit]The† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large_Hadron_Collider" \o "Large Hadron Collider" Large Hadron Collider†experiments represent about 150 million sensors delivering data 40 million times per second. There are nearly 600 million collisions per second. After filtering and refraining from recording more than 99.999% of these streams, there are 100 collisions of interest per second. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-28" [28] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-29" [29] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-nature-30" [30]As a result, only working with less than 0.001% of the sensor stream data, the data flow from all four LHC experiments represents 25 petabytes annual rate before replication (as of 2012). This becomes nearly 200 petabytes after replication.If all sensor data were to be recorded in LHC, the data flow would be extremely hard to work with. The data flow would exceed 150 million petabytes annual rate, or nearly 500 HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exabyte" \o "Exabyte" exabytes†per day, before replication. To put the number in perspective, this is equivalent to 500† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quintillion" \o "Quintillion" quintillion†(5◊1020) bytes per day, almost 200 times higher than all the other sources combined in the world.Science and research[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=3" \o "Edit section: Science and research" edit]When the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sloan_Digital_Sky_Survey" \o "Sloan Digital Sky Survey" Sloan Digital Sky Survey†(SDSS) began collecting astronomical data in 2000, it amassed more in its first few weeks than all data collected in the history of astronomy. Continuing at a rate of about 200 GB per night, SDSS has amassed more than 140 terabytes of information. When the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Large_Synoptic_Survey_Telescope" \o "Large Synoptic Survey Telescope" Large Synoptic Survey Telescope, successor to SDSS, comes online in 2016 it is anticipated to acquire that amount of data every five days. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-Economist-5" [5]Decoding the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Human_Genome_Project" \o "Human Genome Project" human genome†originally took 10 years to process, now it can be achieved in less than a week†: the DNA sequencers have divided the sequencing cost by 10,000 in the last ten years, which is 100 times faster than the reduction in cost predicted by† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moore%27s_Law" \o "Moore's Law" Moore's Law. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-31" [31]The† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nasa" \o "Nasa" NASA†Center for Climate Simulation (NCCS) stores 32 petabytes of climate observations and simulations on the Discover supercomputing cluster. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-32" [32]Government[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=4" \o "Edit section: Government" edit]In 2012, the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Presidency_of_Barack_Obama" \o "Presidency of Barack Obama" Obama administration†announced the Big Data Research and Development Initiative, which explored how big data could be used to address important problems faced by the government. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-WH_Big_Data-33" [33]†The initiative was composed of 84 different big data programs spread across six departments. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-34" [34]Big data analysis played a large role in† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barack_Obama" \o "Barack Obama" Barack Obama's successful† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barack_Obama_presidential_campaign,_2012" \o "Barack Obama presidential campaign, 2012" 2012 re-election campaign. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-35" [35]The† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Federal_Government" \o "United States Federal Government" United States Federal Government†owns six of the ten most powerful supercomputers in the world. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-36" [36]The† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Utah_Data_Center" \o "Utah Data Center" Utah Data Center†is a data center currently being constructed by the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States" \o "United States" United States† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Security_Agency" \o "National Security Agency" National Security Agency. When finished, the facility will be able to handle a large amount of information collected by the NSA over the Internet. The exact amount of storage space is unknown, but more recent sources claim it will be on the order of a few HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exabyte" \o "Exabyte" Exabytes. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-37" [37] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-38" [38] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-39" [39]Private sector[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=5" \o "Edit section: Private sector" edit] HYPERLINK parked outside† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intel_Developer_Forum" \o "Intel Developer Forum" IDF13. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EBay.com" \o "EBay.com" eBay.com†uses two data warehouses at 7.5† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petabytes" \o "Petabytes" petabytes†and 40PB as well as a 40PB† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hadoop" \o "Hadoop" Hadoop†cluster for search, consumer recommendations, and merchandising.† HYPERLINK "http://www.itnews.com.au/News/342615,inside-ebay8217s-90pb-data-warehouse.aspx" Inside eBayís 90PB data warehouse HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amazon.com" \o "Amazon.com" Amazon.com†handles millions of back-end operations every day, as well as queries from more than half a million third-party sellers. The core technology that keeps Amazon running is Linux-based and as of 2005 they had the worldís three largest Linux databases, with capacities of 7.8 TB, 18.5 TB, and 24.7 TB. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-40" [40] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walmart" \o "Walmart" Walmart†handles more than 1 million customer transactions every hour, which are imported into databases estimated to contain more than 2.5 petabytes (2560 terabytes) of data†ñ the equivalent of 167 times the information contained in all the books in the US† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Library_of_Congress" \o "Library of Congress" Library of Congress. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-Economist-5" [5]Facebook handles 50 billion photos from its user base. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-41" [41] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FICO" \o "FICO" FICO†Falcon Credit Card Fraud Detection System protects 2.1 billion active accounts world-wide. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-fico.com-42" [42]The volume of business data worldwide, across all companies, doubles every 1.2 years, according to estimates. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-KnowWPCarey.com-43" [43] HYPERLINK GPS signals from nearly 100 million drivers to help new home buyers determine their typical drive times to and from work throughout various times of the day. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-45" [45]International development[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=6" \o "Edit section: International development. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-46" [46] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-47" [47]†Advancements in big data analysis offer cost-effective opportunities to improve decision-making in critical development areas such as† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Health_care" \o "Health care" health care,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Employment" \o "Employment" employment,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_productivity" \o "Economic productivity" economic productivity, crime, security, and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_disaster" \o "Natural disaster" natural disaster†and resource management. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-HilbertBigData2013-48" [48] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-49" [49]†However, longstanding challenges for developing regions such as inadequate technological infrastructure and economic and human resource scarcity exacerbate existing concerns with big data such as privacy, imperfect methodology, and interoperability issues. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-HilbertBigData2013-48" [48]Market[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=7" \o "Edit section: Market" edit]"Big Data" has increased the demand of information management specialists in that† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_AG" \o "Software AG" Software AG,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oracle_Corporation" \o "Oracle Corporation" Oracle Corporation,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IBM" \o "IBM" IBM,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Microsoft" \o "Microsoft" Microsoft,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SAP_AG" \o "SAP AG" SAP,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EMC_Corporation" \o "EMC Corporation" EMC,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HP" \o "HP" HP†and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dell" \o "Dell" Dell†have spent more than $15 billion on software firms only specializing in data management and analytics. In 2010, this industry on its own was worth more than $100 billion and was growing at almost 10†percent a year: about twice as fast as the software business as a whole. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-Economist-5" [5]Developed economies make increasing use of data-intensive technologies. There are 4.6 billion mobile-phone subscriptions worldwide and there are between 1 billion and 2 billion people accessing the internet. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-Economist-5" [5]†Between 1990 and 2005, more than 1 billion people worldwide entered the middle class which means more and more people who gain money will become more literate which in turn leads to information growth. The world's effective capacity to exchange information through† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telecommunication" \o "Telecommunication" telecommunication†networks was 281† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petabytes" \o "Petabytes" petabytes†in 1986, 471† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petabytes" \o "Petabytes" petabytes†in 1993, 2.2 exabytes in 2000, 65† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exabytes" \o "Exabytes" exabytes†in 2007 HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-HilbertLopez2011-15" [15]†and it is predicted that the amount of traffic flowing over the internet will reach 667 exabytes annually by 2014. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-Economist-5" [5]†It is estimated that one third of the globally stored information is in the form of alphanumeric text and still image data, HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-HilbertContent-50" [50]†which is the format most useful for most big data applications. This also shows the potential of yet unused data (i.e. in the form of video and audio content).Big Data Software: HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hadoop" \o "Hadoop" Hadoop†- Apache Foundation HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MongoDB" \o "MongoDB" MongoDB†- MongoDB, Inc HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Splunk" \o "Splunk" Splunk†- Splunk IncArchitecture[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=8" \o "Edit section: Architecture" edit]In 2004, Google published a paper on a process called† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MapReduce" \o "MapReduce" MapReduce†that used such an architecture. The MapReduce framework provides a parallel processing model and associated implementation to process huge amount of data. With MapReduce, queries are split and distributed across parallel nodes and processed in parallel (the Map step). The results are then gathered and delivered (the Reduce step). The framework was very successful, HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-51" [51]†so others wanted to replicate the algorithm. Therefore, an implementation of the MapReduce framework was adopted by an Apache open source project named† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_Hadoop" \o "Apache Hadoop" Hadoop. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-52" [52] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MIKE2.0_Methodology" \o "MIKE2.0 Methodology" MIKE2.0†is an open approach to information management that acknowledges the need for revisions due to big data implications in an article titled "Big Data Solution Offering". HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-53" [53]The methodology addresses handling big data in terms of useful† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation" \o "Permutation" permutations†of data sources,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complexity" \o "Complexity" complexity†in interrelationships, and difficulty in deleting (or modifying) individual records. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-54" [54]Recent studies show that the use of a multiple layer architecture is an option for dealing with Big Data. The Distributed Parallel architecture distributes data across multiple processing units and parallel processing units provide data much faster, by improving processing speeds. This type of architecture inserts data into a parallel DBMS, which implements the use of MapReduce and Hadoop frameworks. This type of framework looks to make the processing power transparent to the end user by using a front end application server. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-55" [55]Technologies[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=9" \o "Edit section: Technologies" edit]Big data requires exceptional technologies to efficiently process large quantities of data within tolerable elapsed times. A 2011† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/McKinsey_%26_Company" \o "McKinsey & Company" McKinsey†report HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-56" [56]†suggests suitable technologies include† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A/B_testing" \o "A/B testing" A/B testing,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crowdsourcing" \o "Crowdsourcing" crowdsourcing,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_fusion" \o "Data fusion" data fusion†and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_integration" \o "Data integration" integration,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetic_algorithms" \o "Genetic algorithms" genetic algorithms,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machine_learning" \o "Machine learning" machine learning,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_language_processing" \o "Natural language processing" natural language processing,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signal_processing" \o "Signal processing" signal processing,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simulation" \o "Simulation" simulation,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_series_analysis" \o "Time series analysis" time series analysis†and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visualization_(computer_graphics)" \o "Visualization (computer graphics)" visualisation. Multidimensional big data can also be represented as† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tensor" \o "Tensor" tensors, which can be more efficiently handled by tensor-based computation, HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-57" [57]†such as HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multilinear_subspace_learning" \o "Multilinear subspace learning" multilinear subspace learning. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-MSLsurvey-58" [58]†Additional technologies being applied to big data include massively parallel-processing ( HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massive_parallel_processing" \o "Massive parallel processing" MPP) databases,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Search-based_application" \o "Search-based application" search-based applications, data-mining grids, distributed file systems, distributed databases, cloud based infrastructure (applications, storage and computing resources) and the Internet.[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" \o "Wikipedia:Citation needed" citation needed]Some but not all† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massive_parallel_processing" \o "Massive parallel processing" MPP†relational databases have the ability to store and manage petabytes of data. Implicit is the ability to load, monitor, back up, and optimize the use of the large data tables in the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RDBMS" \o "RDBMS" RDBMS. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-59" [59] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DARPA" \o "DARPA" DARPAís† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topological_Data_Analysis" \o "Topological Data Analysis" Topological Data Analysis†program seeks the fundamental structure of massive data sets and in 2008 the technology went public with the launch of a company called HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ayasdi" \o "Ayasdi" Ayasdi. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-60" [60]The practitioners of big data analytics processes are generally hostile to slower shared storage, HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-61" [61]†preferring direct-attached storage ( HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Direct-attached_storage" \o "Direct-attached storage" DAS) in its various forms from solid state drive ( HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ssd" \o "Ssd" SSD) to high capacity† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serial_ATA" \o "Serial ATA" SATA†disk buried inside parallel processing nodes. The perception of shared storage architecturesó HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Storage_area_network" \o "Storage area network" Storage area network†(SAN) and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network-attached_storage" \o "Network-attached storage" Network-attached storage†(NAS) óis that they are relatively slow, complex, and expensive. These qualities are not consistent with big data analytics systems that thrive on system performance, commodity infrastructure, and low cost.Real or near-real time information delivery is one of the defining characteristics of big data analytics. Latency is therefore avoided whenever and wherever possible. Data in memory is goodódata on spinning disk at the other end of a† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiber_connector" \o "Fiber connector" FC† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Storage_area_network" \o "Storage area network" SAN†connection is not. The cost of a† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Storage_area_network" \o "Storage area network" SAN†at the scale needed for analytics applications is very much higher than other storage techniques.There are advantages as well as disadvantages to shared storage in big data analytics, but big data analytics practitioners as of 2011†did not favour it. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-62" [62]Research activities[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=10" \o "Edit section: Research activities" edit]Encrypted search & cluster formation in Big Data is set for the demonstration in March 2014 at American Society of Engineering Education. Gautam Siwach engaged at Tackling the challenges of Big Data by† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MIT_Computer_Science_and_Artificial_Intelligence_Laboratory" \o "MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory" MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory†and Dr. Amir Esmailpour at UNH Research Group investigated the key features of big data as formation of clusters and their interconnections. They focused on the security of big data and the actual orientation of the term towards the presence of different type of data in an encrypted form at cloud interface by providing the raw definitions and real time examples within the technology. Moreover, they proposed an approach for identifying the encoding technique to advance towards an expedited search over encrypted text leading to the security enhancements in big data. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-63" [63]In March 2012, The White House announced a national "Big Data Initiative" that consisted of six Federal departments and agencies committing more than $200 million to big data research projects. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-64" [64]The initiative included a National Science Foundation "Expeditions in Computing" grant of $10 million over 5 years to the AMPLab HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-65" [65]†at the University of California, Berkeley. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-66" [66]The AMPLab also received funds from† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DARPA" \o "DARPA" DARPA, and over a dozen industrial sponsors and uses big data to attack a wide range of problems from predicting traffic congestion HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-67" [67]†to fighting cancer. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-68" [68]The White House Big Data Initiative also included a commitment by the Department of Energy to provide $25 million in funding over 5 years to establish the Scalable Data Management, Analysis and Visualization (SDAV) Institute, HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-69" [69]†led by the Energy Departmentís† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lawrence_Berkeley_National_Laboratory" \o "Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory" Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory. The SDAV Institute aims to bring together the expertise of six national laboratories and seven universities to develop new tools to help scientists manage and visualize data on the Departmentís supercomputers.The U.S. state of† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massachusetts" \o "Massachusetts" Massachusetts†announced the Massachusetts Big Data Initiative in May 2012, which provides funding from the state government and private companies to a variety of research institutions. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-70" [70]†The† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology" \o "Massachusetts Institute of Technology" Massachusetts Institute of Technology†hosts the Intel Science and Technology Center for Big Data in the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MIT_Computer_Science_and_Artificial_Intelligence_Laboratory" \o "MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory" MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, combining government, corporate, and institutional funding and research efforts. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-71" [71]The European Commission is funding a 2-year-long† HYPERLINK "http://big-project.eu/" Big Data Public Private Forum†through their† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Seventh_Framework_Program&action=edit&redlink=1" \o "Seventh Framework Program (page does not exist)" Seventh Framework Program†to engage companies, academics and other stakeholders in discussing big data issues. The project aims to define a strategy in terms of research and innovation to guide supporting actions from the European Commission in the successful implementation of the Big Data economy. Outcomes of this project will be used as input for† HYPERLINK "http://ec.europa.eu/research/horizon2020/index_en.cfm?pg=h2020" Horizon 2020, their next† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Framework_Programmes_for_Research_and_Technological_Development" \o "Framework Programmes for Research and Technological Development" framework program. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-72" [72]The British government announced in March 2014 the founding of the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Turing" \o "Alan Turing" Alan Turing†Institute, named after the computer pioneer and code-breaker, which will focus on new ways of collecting and analysing large sets of data. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-73" [73]At the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Waterloo_Stratford_Campus" \o "University of Waterloo Stratford Campus" University of Waterloo Stratford Campus†Canadian Open Data Experience (CODE) Inspiration Day, it was demonstrated how using Data Visualization techniques can increase the understanding and appeal of Big Data sets in order to communicate a story to the world. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-74" [74]In order to make manufacturing more competitive in the United States (and globe), there is a need to integrate more American ingenuity and innovation into manufacturing†; Therefore, National Science Foundation has granted the Industry University cooperative research† HYPERLINK "http://www.imscenter.net/" center for Intelligent Maintenance Systems (IMS)†at† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Cincinnati" \o "University of Cincinnati" university of Cincinnati†to focus on developing advanced predictive tools and techniques to be applicable in Big Data environment. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-SMELettersPaper-75" [75] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-76" [76]†In May 2013, IMS Center held an industry advisory board meeting focusing on Big Data where presenters from various industrial companies discussed their concerns, issues and future goals in Big Data environment.Computational social science†ó† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tobias_Preis" \o "Tobias Preis" Tobias Preis†et al.†used† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_Trends" \o "Google Trends" Google Trends†data to demonstrate that Internet users from countries with a higher per capita gross domestic product (GDP) are more likely to search for information about the future than information about the past. The findings suggest there may be a link between online behaviour and real-world economic indicators. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-77" [77] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-78" [78] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-79" [79]†The authors of the study examined Google queries logs made by ratio of the volume of searches for the coming year (ë2011í) to the volume of searches for the previous year (ë2009í), which they call the ë HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Future_orientation_index" \o "Future orientation index" future orientation indexí. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-80" [80]†They compared the future orientation index to the per capita GDP of each country and found a strong tendency for countries in which Google users enquire more about the future to exhibit a higher GDP. The results hint that there may potentially be a relationship between the economic success of a country and the information-seeking behavior of its citizens captured in big data. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tobias_Preis" \o "Tobias Preis" Tobias Preis†and his colleagues† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Helen_Susannah_Moat&action=edit&redlink=1" \o "Helen Susannah Moat (page does not exist)" Helen Susannah Moat†and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H._Eugene_Stanley" \o "H. Eugene Stanley" H. Eugene Stanley†introduced a method to identify online precursors for stock market moves, using trading strategies based on search volume data provided by Google Trends. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-81" [81]†Their analysis of† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google" \o "Google" Google†search volume for 98 terms of varying financial relevance, published in† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_Reports" \o "Scientific Reports" Scientific Reports, HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-82" [82]†suggests that increases in search volume for financially relevant search terms tend to precede large losses in financial markets. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-83" [83] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-84" [84] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-85" [85] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-86" [86] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-87" [87] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-88" [88] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-89" [89] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-90" [90]Applications[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=11" \o "Edit section: Applications" edit]Manufacturing[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=12" \o "Edit section: Manufacturing" edit]Based on TCS 2013 Global Trend Study, huge improvements in supply planning and boost product quality is the greatest benefit of Big Data for manufacturing. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-91" [91]†Big Data provides an infrastructure for transparency in manufacturing industry, which is the ability to unravel uncertainties such as inconsistent component performance and availability. Predictive manufacturing as an applicable approach toward near-zero downtime and transparency requires vast amount of data and advanced prediction tools for a systematic process of data into useful information. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-92" [92]†A conceptual framework of predictive manufacturing begins with data acquisition where different type of sensory data is available to acquire such as acoustics, vibration, pressure, current, voltage and controller data. Vast amount of sensory data in addition to historical data construct the ìBig Dataî in manufacturing. The generated Big Data acts as the input into predictive tools and preventive strategies such as† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prognostics" \o "Prognostics" Prognostics and Health Management†(PHM). HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-SMELettersPaper-75" [75]Critique[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=13" \o "Edit section: Critique" edit]Critiques of the big data paradigm come in two flavors, those that question the implications of the approach itself, and those that question the way it is currently done. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Big_data_cartoon_t_gregorius.jpg"  INCLUDEPICTURE "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b3/Big_data_cartoon_t_gregorius.jpg/220px-Big_data_cartoon_t_gregorius.jpg" \* MERGEFORMATINET  HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Big_data_cartoon_t_gregorius.jpg" \o "Enlarge"  INCLUDEPICTURE "http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.24wmf1/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" \* MERGEFORMATINET Cartoon critical of big data applicationCritiques of the big data paradigm[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=14" \o "Edit section: Critiques of the big data paradigm" edit]"A crucial problem is that we do not know much about the underlying empirical micro-processes that lead to the emergence of the[se] typical network characteristics of Big Data". HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-Editorial-20" [20]†In their critique, Snijders, Matzat, and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulf-Dietrich_Reips" \o "Ulf-Dietrich Reips" Reips†point out that often very strong assumptions are made about mathematical properties that may not at all reflect what is really going on at the level of micro-processes. Mark Graham has leveled broad critiques at† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Anderson_(writer)" \o "Chris Anderson (writer)" Chris Anderson's assertion that big data will spell the end of theory: focusing in particular on the notion that big data will always need to be contextualized in their social, economic and political contexts. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-93" [93]†Even as companies invest eight- and nine-figure sums to derive insight from information streaming in from suppliers and customers, less than 40% of employees have sufficiently mature processes and skills to do so. To overcome this insight deficit, "big data", no matter how comprehensive or well analyzed, needs to be complemented by "big judgment", according to an article in the Harvard Business Review. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-94" [94]Much in the same line, it has been pointed out that the decisions based on the analysis of big data are inevitably "informed by the world as it was in the past, or, at best, as it currently is". HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-HilbertBigData2013-48" [48]†Fed by a large number of data on past experiences, algorithms can predict future development if the future is similar to the past. If the systems dynamics of the future change, the past can say little about the future. For this, it would be necessary to have a thorough understanding of the systems dynamic, which implies theory. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-95" [95]†As a response to this critique it has been suggested to combine big data approaches with computer simulations, such as† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agent-based_model" \o "Agent-based model" agent-based models, for example. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-HilbertBigData2013-48" [48]Agent-based models are increasingly getting better in predicting the outcome of social complexities of even unknown future scenarios through computer simulations that are based on a collection of mutually interdependent algorithms. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-96" [96] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-97" [97]†In addition, use of multivariate methods that probe for the latent structure of the data, such as† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factor_analysis" \o "Factor analysis" factor analysis†and HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cluster_analysis" \o "Cluster analysis" cluster analysis, have proven useful as analytic approaches that go well beyond the bi-variate approaches (cross-tabs) typically employed with smaller data sets.In health and biology, conventional scientific approaches are based on experimentation. For these approaches, the limiting factor are the relevant data that can confirm or refute the initial hypothesis. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-98" [98]†A new postulate is accepted now in biosciences: the information provided by the data in huge volumes ( HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omics" \o "Omics" omics) without prior hypothesis is complementary and sometimes necessary to conventional approaches based on experimentation. In the massive approaches it is the formulation of a relevant hypothesis to explain the data that is the limiting factor. The search logic is reversed and the limits of induction ("Glory of Science and Philosophy scandal",† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C._D._Broad" \o "C. D. Broad" C. D. Broad, 1926) to be considered. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Consumer_privacy" \o "Consumer privacy" Privacy†advocates are concerned about the threat to privacy represented by increasing storage and integration of† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Personally_identifiable_information" \o "Personally identifiable information" personally identifiable information; expert panels have released various policy recommendations to conform practice to expectations of privacy. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-99" [99] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-100" [100] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-101" [101]Critiques of big data execution[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=15" \o "Edit section: Critiques of big data execution" edit]Researcher† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Danah_Boyd" \o "Danah Boyd" Danah Boyd†has raised concerns about the use of big data in† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Science" \o "Science" science†neglecting principles such as choosing a† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sampling_(statistics)" \o "Sampling (statistics)" representative sample†by being too concerned about actually handling the huge amounts of data. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-danah-102" [102]†This approach may lead to results† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bias_(statistics)" \o "Bias (statistics)" bias†in one way or another. Integration across heterogeneous data resources†ó some that might be considered "big data" and others not†ó presents formidable logistical as well as analytical challenges, but many researchers argue that such integrations are likely to represent the most promising new frontiers in science. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-103" [103]†In the provocative article "Critical Questions for Big Data", HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-danah2-104" [104]†the authors title Big Data a part of† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mythology" \o "Mythology" Mythology: "large data sets offer a higher form of intelligence and knowledge [...], with the aura of truth, objectivity, and accuracy". Users of Big Data are often "lost in the sheer volume of numbers", and "working with Big Data is still subjective, and what it quantifies does not necessarily have a closer claim on objective truth". HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-danah2-104" [104]Big data is a† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buzzword" \o "Buzzword" buzzword†and a "vague term", HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-ft-harford-105" [105]†but at the same time an "obsession" HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-ft-harford-105" [105]†with entrepreneurs, consultants, scientists and the media. Big data showcases such as HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_Flu_Trends" \o "Google Flu Trends" Google Flu Trends†failed to deliver good predictions in recent years, overstating the flu outbreaks by a factor of two. Similarly,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academy_awards" \o "Academy awards" Academy awards†and election predictions solely based on Twitter were more often off than on target. Big data often poses the same challenges as small data; and adding more data does not solve problems of bias, but may emphasize other problems. In particular data sources such as Twitter are not representative of the overall population, and results drawn from such sources may then lead to wrong conclusions.† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_Translate" \o "Google Translate" Google Translate†- which is based on big data statistical analysis of text - does a remarkably good job at translating web pages, but for specialized domains the results may be badly off. On the other hand, big data may also introduce new problems, such as the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_comparisons_problem" \o "Multiple comparisons problem" multiple comparisons problem: simultaneously testing a large set of hypotheses is likely to produce many false results that mistakenly appear to be significant. Ioannidis argued that "most published research findings are false"† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-Ioannidis-106" [106]†due to essentially the same effect: when many scientific teams and researchers each perform many experiments (i.e. process a big amount of scientific data; although not with big data technology), the likelihood of a "singificant" result being actually false grows fast - even more so, when only positive results are published.Benefits[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=16" \o "Edit section: Benefits" edit]Individual HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-107" [107][ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=17" \o "Edit section: Individual[107]" edit]Big data analysis provides a direct benefit to those individuals whose information is being used. For example, the high degree of customization pursued by Netflix and Amazon, which recommend films and products to consumers based on analysis of their previous interactions. Data analysis benefits consumers and has been justified without solicitation of explicit agreement. Similarly, Comcastís decision in 2010 to proactively monitor its customersí computers to detect malware,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-108" [108]and more recent decisions by Internet service providers including Comcast, AT&T, and Verizon to reach out to consumers to report potential malware infections, were intended to directly benefit consumers.† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-109" [109]†Also Googleís autocomplete and translate are based on comprehensive data collection and real time analysis.Community HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-110" [110][ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=18" \o "Edit section: Community[110]" edit]The collection and use of an individualís data benefits not only individual, but also community, such as users of a similar product of residents of a geographical area. Think about Internet browser crash reports, which few users opt into not so much because of real privacy concerns but rater due to a belief that others will do the job for them. Those users who do agree to send crash reports benefit not only themselves, but also other users of the same product. Similarly, individuals who report drug side effects confer a benefit to other existing and prospective users.Organizations HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-111" [111][ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=19" \o "Edit section: Organizations[111]" edit]Big data analysis often benefits those organizations that collect and harness the data. Data-driven profits may be viewed as enhancing allocative efficiency by facilitating the ëfreeí economy.† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-112" [112]†The emergence, expansion, and widespread use of innovative products and services at decreasing marginal costs have revolutionized global economies and societal structures, facilitating access to technology and knowledge† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-113" [113]†and fomenting social change.† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-114" [114]†With more data, businesses can optimize distribution methods, efficiently allocate credit, and robustly combat fraud, benefitting consumers as a whole.† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-115" [115]†But in the absence of individual value or broader societal gain, others may consider enhanced business profits to be a mere value transfer from individuals whose data is being exploited. In economic terms, such profits create distributional gains to some actors as opposed to driving allocative efficiency.Society HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_note-116" [116][ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=20" \o "Edit section: Society[116]" edit]Some data uses benefit society at large, for example, data mining for purposes of national security. When weighting the benefits of national security driven policies, the effects should be assessed at a broad societal level. Similarly, data usage for fraud detection in the payment card industry helps facilitate safe, secure, and frictionless transactions, benefiting society as a whole. And large-scale analysis of geo-location data has been used for urban planning, disaster recovery, and optimization of energy consumption.See also[ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Big_data&action=edit&section=21" \o "Edit section: See also" edit] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Computer-aj_aj_ashton_01.svg"  O'Reilly Media. p.†257.† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" \o "International Standard Book Number" ISBN† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-596-15711-1" \o "Special:BookSources/978-0-596-15711-1" 978-0-596-15711-1.^† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_ref-HilbertLopez2011_15-0" Jump up to:a† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_ref-HilbertLopez2011_15-1" b† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "CITEREFHilbertL.C3.B3pez2011" Hilbert & LÛpez 2011 HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_ref-16" Jump up^† HYPERLINK "http://www.ibm.com/big-data/us/en/" "IBM What is big data? ó Bringing big data to the enterprise". www.ibm.com. (2012). ëBig Dataí: Big gaps of knowledge in the field of Internet.†International Journal of Internet Science, 7, 1-5. HYPERLINK "http://www.ijis.net/ijis7_1/ijis7_1_editorial.html" http://www.ijis.net/ijis7_1/ijis7_1_editorial.html HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_data" \l "cite_ref-21" Jump up^†Laney, Douglas.† HYPERLINK "http://blogs.gartner.com/doug-laney/files/2012/01/ad949-3D-Data-Management-Controlling-Data-Volume-Velocity-and-Variety.pdf" "3D Data Management: Controlling Data Volume, Velocity and Variety". Gartner. K. Rowling" J. K. Rowling. The series, named after the titular character, chronicles the adventures of a young† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magician_(fantasy)" \o "Magician (fantasy)" wizard,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_(character)" \o "Harry Potter (character)" Harry Potter, and his friends† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ron_Weasley" \o "Ron Weasley" Ronald Weasley†and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermione_Granger" \o "Hermione Granger" Hermione Granger, all of whom are students at† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hogwarts_School_of_Witchcraft_and_Wizardry" \o "Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry" Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry. The main† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Story_arc" \o "Story arc" story arc†concerns Harry's quest to overcome the Dark wizard† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lord_Voldemort" \o "Lord Voldemort" Lord Voldemort, who aims to become immortal, conquer the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_universe" \o "Harry Potter universe" wizarding world, subjugate non-magical people, and destroy all those who stand in his way, especially Harry Potter.Since the release of the first novel,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Philosopher%27s_Stone" \o "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone, on 30 June 1997, the books have gained immense popularity, critical acclaim, and commercial success worldwide. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-2" [2]†The series has also had some share of criticism, including concern for the increasingly dark tone. As of July 2013, the book series had sold between 400 and 450 million copies, making it one of the HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_best-selling_books" \o "List of best-selling books" best-selling book series in history, and had been† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_in_translation" \o "Harry Potter in translation" translated into 73 languages. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-Translations_for_Harry_Potter-3" [3] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-PotterStats20130731-4" [4]†The last four books consecutively set records as the fastest-selling books in history, with the final instalment selling approximately 11 million copies in the United States within the first twenty-four hours of its release.A series of many† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genre" \o "Genre" genres, including† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fantasy" \o "Fantasy" fantasy,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coming_of_age" \o "Coming of age" coming of age, and the British† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/School_story" \o "School story" school story, (with elements of† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mystery_(fiction)" \o "Mystery (fiction)" mystery,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thriller_(genre)" \o "Thriller (genre)" thriller,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adventure_novel" \o "Adventure novel" adventure, and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Romance_novel" \o "Romance novel" romance), it has many cultural meanings and references. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-meanings-5" [5]†According to Rowling, the main† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theme_(literature)" \o "Theme (literature)" theme†is death. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-Geordie_Greig-6" [6]†There are also many other themes in the series, such as prejudice and corruption. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-QuickQuoteQuill-7" [7]The series was originally printed in English by two major publishers,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bloomsbury_Publishing" \o "Bloomsbury Publishing" Bloomsbury†in the United Kingdom and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scholastic_Corporation" \o "Scholastic Corporation" Scholastic Press†in the United States. The books have since been published by many publishers worldwide. The books, with the seventh book split into two parts, have been made into an eight-part† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_(film_series)" \o "Harry Potter (film series)" film series†by† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warner_Bros." \o "Warner Bros." Warner Bros. Pictures, the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_highest-grossing_franchises_and_film_series" \o "List of highest-grossing franchises and film series" highest-grossing film series†of all time. The series also originated much† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tie-in" \o "Tie-in" tie-in†merchandise, making the†Harry Potter†brand worth in excess of $15†billion. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-HP_brand_worth-8" [8]Thanks to the success of the books and films,†Harry Potter†has also been used for a theme park,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wizarding_World_of_Harry_Potter_(Islands_of_Adventure)" \o "The Wizarding World of Harry Potter (Islands of Adventure)" The Wizarding World of Harry Potter†in†
