Mexican director† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfonso_Cuar%C3%B3n" \o "Alfonso CuarÛn" Alfonso CuarÛn†took over the job, and after shooting in 2003, the film was released on 4 June 2004. Due to the fourth film beginning its production before the third's release,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Newell_(director)" \o "Mike Newell (director)" Mike Newell†was chosen as the director for† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Goblet_of_Fire_(film)" \o "Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (film)" Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire, released on 18 November 2005. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-140" [140]†Newell became the first British director of the series, with television director† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Yates" \o "David Yates" David Yates†following suit after he was chosen to helm HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Order_of_the_Phoenix_(film)" \o "Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (film)" Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix. Production began in January 2006 and the film was released the following year in July 2007. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-141" [141]†After executives were "really delighted" with his work on the film, Yates was selected to direct† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Half-Blood_Prince_(film)" \o "Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (film)" Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince, which was released on 15 July 2009. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-142" [142] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-yates-director-scifi-143" [143] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-date_change-144" [144] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-release-date-hbp-film-145" [145] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Gringotts_Wizarding_Bank_2.jpg"  INCLUDEPICTURE "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Gringotts_Wizarding_Bank_2.jpg/170px-Gringotts_Wizarding_Bank_2.jpg" \* MERGEFORMATINET  HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Gringotts_Wizarding_Bank_2.jpg" \o "Enlarge"  INCLUDEPICTURE "http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.24wmf1/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" \* MERGEFORMATINET Gringotts Wizarding Bank as seen in the film series.In March 2008, Warner Bros. on the two-partDeathly Hallows, alongside† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Heyman" \o "David Heyman" David Heyman†and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Barron_(film_producer)" \o "David Barron (film producer)" David Barron. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-148" [148]†The†Harry Potter†films have been top-rank box office hits, with all eight releases on the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_highest-grossing_films" \o "List of highest-grossing films" list of highest-grossing films worldwide.†Philosopher's Stone†was the highest-grossing†Harry Potter†film up until the release of the final instalment of the series,†Deathly Hallows, while†Prisoner of Azkaban†grossed the least. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-149" [149]†As well as being a financial success, the film series has also been a† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Critical_response_to_the_Harry_Potter_films&action=edit&redlink=1" \o "Critical response to the Harry Potter films (page does not exist)" success among film critics. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-150" [150] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-151" [151]Opinions of the films are generally divided among fans, with one group preferring the more faithful approach of the first two films, and another group preferring the more stylised character-driven approach of the later films. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-152" [152]†Rowling has been constantly supportive of all the films and evaluated†Deathly Hallows†as her "favourite one" in the series. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-jk-on-ps-film-153" [153] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-jk-on-poa-film-154" [154] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-jk-on-gof-film-155" [155] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-156" [156]†She wrote on her website of the changes in the book-to-film transition, "It is simply impossible to incorporate every one of my storylines into a film that has to be kept under four hours long. Obviously films have restrictions novels do not have, constraints of time and budget; I can create dazzling effects relying on nothing but the interaction of my own and my readers' imaginations". HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-157" [157]At the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/64th_British_Academy_Film_Awards" \o "64th British Academy Film Awards" 64th British Academy Film Awards†in February 2011, Rowling was joined by producers David Heyman and David Barron along with directors David Yates, Alfonso CuarÛn and Mike Newell in collecting the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/64th_British_Academy_Film_Awards" \l "Michael_Balcon_Award_for_Outstanding_British_Contribution_to_Cinema" \o "64th British Academy Film Awards" Michael Balcon Award for Outstanding British Contribution to Cinema†on behalf of all the films in the series. Actors† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rupert_Grint" \o "Rupert Grint" Rupert Grint†and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emma_Watson" \o "Emma Watson" Emma Watson, who play main characters† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ron_Weasley" \o "Ron Weasley" Ron Weasley†and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermione_Granger" \o "Hermione Granger" Hermione Granger, were also in attendance. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-158" [158] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-159" [159]GamesThere are eleven†Harry Potter†video games, eight of which correspond with the films and books, and three other spin-offs. The film/book based games are produced by† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_Arts" \o "Electronic Arts" Electronic Arts, as was† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter:_Quidditch_World_Cup" \o "Harry Potter: Quidditch World Cup" Harry Potter: Quidditch World Cup, with the game version of the first entry in the series,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Philosopher%27s_Stone_(video_game)" \o "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (video game)" Philosopher's Stone, being released in November 2001. The video games are released to coincide with the films, containing scenery and details from the films as well as the tone and spirit of the books. Objectives usually occur in and around† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hogwarts" \o "Hogwarts" Hogwarts, along with various other magical areas. The story and design of the games follows the selected film's characterisation and plot; EA worked closely with Warner Brothers to include scenes from the films. The last game in the series,†Deathly Hallows, was split with† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Deathly_Hallows_-_Part_1_(video_game)" \o "Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows - Part 1 (video game)" Part 1†released in November 2010 and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Deathly_Hallows_-_Part_2_(video_game)" \o "Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows - Part 2 (video game)" Part 2†debuting on consoles in July 2011. The two-part game forms the first entry to convey an intense theme of action and violence, with the gameplay revolving around a third-person shooter style format. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-160" [160] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-161" [161]†The other spin-offs games,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LEGO_Harry_Potter:_Years_1%E2%80%934" \o "LEGO Harry Potter: Years 1ñ4" LEGO Harry Potter: Years 1ñ4†and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lego_Harry_Potter:_Years_5%E2%80%937" \o "Lego Harry Potter: Years 5ñ7" LEGO Harry Potter: Years 5ñ7†are developed by† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traveller%27s_Tales" \o "Traveller's Tales" Traveller's Tales†and published by† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warner_Bros._Interactive_Entertainment" \o "Warner Bros. Interactive Entertainment" Warner Bros. Interactive Entertainment. A number of other non-interactive media games have been released; board games such as† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cluedo" \o "Cluedo" Cluedo†Harry Potter Edition,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scene_It%3F" \o "Scene It?" Scene It?†Harry Potter†and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lego_Harry_Potter" \o "Lego Harry Potter" Lego Harry Potter†models, which are influenced by the themes of both the novels and films.2001:† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Philosopher%27s_Stone_(video_game)" \o "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (video game)" Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone2002:† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Chamber_of_Secrets_(video_game)" \o "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets (video game)" Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets2004:† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Prisoner_of_Azkaban_(video_game)" \o "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (video game)" Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban2005:† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Goblet_of_Fire_(video_game)" \o "Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire (video game)" Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire2007:† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Order_of_the_Phoenix_(video_game)" \o "Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix (video game)" Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix2009:† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Half-Blood_Prince_(video_game)" \o "Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince (video game)" Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince2010:† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter_and_the_Deathly_Hallows_%E2%80%93_Part_1_(video_game)" \o ñ Part 2AudiobooksAll seven†Harry Potter†books have been released in unabridged audiobook versions, with† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_Fry" \o "Stephen Fry" Stephen Fry†reading for listeners in the UK, and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jim_Dale" \o "Jim Dale" Jim Dale†voicing the series for the American editions. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-162" [162] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-163" [163]Stage productionOn 20 December 2013 J. K. Rowling announced that she was working on a Harry Potterñbased play for which she would be one of the producers. In her statement, the author said that the play will "explore the previously untold story of Harry's early years as an orphan and outcast". British theatre producers† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonia_Friedman" \o "Sonia Friedman" Sonia Friedman†and† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colin_Callender" \o "Colin Callender" Colin Callender†will be the co-producers. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-164" [164] HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-165" [165]AttractionsUnited StatesMain article:† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wizarding_World_of_Harry_Potter_(Islands_of_Adventure)" \o "The Wizarding World of Harry Potter (Islands of Adventure)" The Wizarding World of Harry Potter (Islands of Adventure) HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wizarding_World_of_Harry_Potter_Castle.jpg"  INCLUDEPICTURE "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c4/Wizarding_World_of_Harry_Potter_Castle.jpg/220px-Wizarding_World_of_Harry_Potter_Castle.jpg" \* MERGEFORMATINET  HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Wizarding_World_of_Harry_Potter_Castle.jpg" \o "Enlarge"  INCLUDEPICTURE "http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.24wmf1/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" \* MERGEFORMATINET Hogwarts Castle as depicted in the Wizarding World of Harry Potter located in Universal Orlando Resort's Island of Adventure.After the success of the films and books, Universal and Warner Brothers announced they would create "The Wizarding World of Harry Potter," a new†Harry Potter-themed expansion to the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islands_of_Adventure" \o "Islands of Adventure" Islands of Adventure†theme park at† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_Orlando_Resort" \o "Universal Orlando Resort" Universal Orlando Resort†in Florida. The new land, promoted as the seventh themed "island" of the park, was built from land reserved for expansion outside of the park's original border, as well as from much of the existing "island,"† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mythos_(restaurant)" \o "Mythos (restaurant)" The Lost Continent. A soft opening was held at the end of March 2010, with the land opening on 16 June 2010 for reserved guests. The land officially opened to the public on 18 June 2010. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-166" [166]Guests enter the land through a recreation of the Hogsmeade station, HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-167" [167]†leading into the village of† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hogsmeade" \o "Hogsmeade" Hogsmeade, with a† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forced_perspective" \o "Forced perspective" forced-perspectiveHogwarts castle at the very end of the street. The castle contains the expansion's centrepiece attraction,†Harry Potter & the Forbidden Journey,†a† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KUKA" \o "KUKA" KUKA arm†attraction which takes passengers through many realistic scenes influenced by the movies and books, including soaring over Hogwarts, getting involved in a Quidditch match, and having close encounters with dragons, dementors, and the Whomping Willow. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-168" [168]†Other attractions include a twin high-speed rollercoaster named the† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragon_Challenge" \o "Dragon Challenge" Dragon Challenge,†a renovation of the previously existing rollercoaster,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dueling_Dragons" \o "Dueling Dragons" Dueling Dragons, and a family roller coaster called† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flight_of_the_Hippogriff" \o "Flight of the Hippogriff" Flight of the Hippogriff, a renovation of the previously existing ride,† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flight_of_the_Hippogriff" \l "Flying_Unicorn_era" \o "Flight of the Hippogriff" Flying Unicorn. In addition to the three rides are several themed shops and restaurants, heavily inspired by their appearances in the books and films: Honeydukes sells sweets, such as chocolate frogs and†Bertie Bott's Every-Flavour Beans,†Ollivander's†offers personalised magic wands, Zonko's Joke Shop sells various items including Sneakoscopes, and the Three Broomsticks serves food and drink, most notably Butterbeer and pumpkin juice.Developed at a cost of $265 million, the new land "has seen capacity crowds [and] waits of up to two hours just to enter the ... merchandise shop." Islands of Adventure saw a massive increase in attendance following the expansion, seeing gains of as much as 36%, HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-169" [169]†a period during which attendance to competitor resort† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walt_Disney_World" \o "Walt Disney World" Walt Disney World†dropped slightly. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-170" [170]†Disney had itself entered negotiations for a†Harry Potter-themed expansion, but ultimately turned down the opportunity. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-171" [171]United KingdomIn March 2011, Warner Bros. announced plans to build a tourist attraction in the United Kingdom to showcase the†Harry Potter†film series. Warner Bros. Studio Tour London is a behind-the-scenes walking tour featuring authentic sets, costumes and props from the film series. The attraction is located at† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warner_Bros._Studios,_Leavesden" \o "Warner Bros. Studios, Leavesden" Warner Bros. Studios, Leavesden, where all eight of the†Harry Potter†films were made. Warner Bros. constructed two new sound stages to house and showcase the famous sets from each of the British-made productions, following a £100 million investment. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-172" [172]†It opened to the public in March 2012. HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_note-173" [173]See also INCLUDEPICTURE "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Office-book.svg/30px-Office-book.svg.png" \* MERGEFORMATINET  HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book:Harry_Potter" \o "Book:Harry Potter" Book: Harry Potter HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_GrandPr%C3%A9" \o "Mary GrandPrÈ" Mary GrandPrÈ HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Tom_Sawyer_1876_frontispiece.jpg"  INCLUDEPICTURE "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Tom_Sawyer_1876_frontispiece.jpg/15px-Tom_Sawyer_1876_frontispiece.jpg" \* MERGEFORMATINET  HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portal:Children%27s_literature" \o "Portal:Children's literature" Children's literature portal† HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:HP_-_Harry_Potter_wordmark.svg"  INCLUDEPICTURE "http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9b/HP_-_Harry_Potter_wordmark.svg/19px-HP_-_Harry_Potter_wordmark.svg.png" \* MERGEFORMATINET  HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Portal:Harry_Potter" \o "Portal:Harry Potter" Harry Potter portalReferences HYPERLINK "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harry_Potter" \l "cite_ref-1" Jump up^†PETER SVENSSON 27 March 2012 (27 March 2012).† HYPERLINK "http://news.yahoo.com/harry-potter-breaks-e-book-lockdown-205343680.html" "Harry Potter breaks e-book lockdown - Yahoo! From Wall Street to Twitter, the reaction is swift and negative.The price of oil falls, as do the prices of blue-chip stocks like General Electric. The Federal Reserve faces calls to push interest rates lower. The lead headlines in the next dayís papers talk of faltering job growth.But what if all the worries were based on nothing more than random statistical noise? What if the apparent decline in job growth came from the inherent volatility of surveys that rely on samples, like the survey that produces the Labor Departmentís monthly employment estimate?We generated those numbers with a computer, after giving it a simple set of directions: Assume that the economy is adding exactly 150,000 jobs every month, and that the monthly estimates of job growth come with exactly as much statistical noise as the Labor Department says its estimates have.Letís consider how statistical noise might affect our perception of the jobs report in two scenarios: one with steady job growth and one with accelerating job growth.Did you infer a pattern from the chart on the right? If you did, you were reading too much into the jobs numbers. That chart should be a straight line, but weíve added the same amount of sampling error that the jobs report has.Even when the economy is moving in a clear direction, the noise in month-to-month changes can be big enough to obscure any trend. Imagine a different type of year from the one above with constant job growth: one in which true job growth starts at 150,000 jobs in January and accelerates by 15,000 a month to more than 300,000 in December.If you squint, you can see evidence of the upward trend, with stronger growth apparent in the second half of the year. But month by month, you wouldnít have any way of knowing if it was a true acceleration, or just a false signal generated by sampling error.The result of one of the computer simulations was a yearís worth of fluctuating job growth. Two months, June and September, showed job creation below 100,000;      ⁄ € r t ê í î ñ Z \ p r t v   " 8 : < > Ë Í ¯ ˙ ¸ ˛ ˆ ¯     – “ ‰Õ‰¥‰Õ‰Õ‰ó‰Õ‰Õ‰z‰Õ‰Õ‰¥‰Õ‰Õ‰]‰Õ‰Õ‰                 8hy05 hè^ >*B*	CJ  OJ PJ  QJ ^J aJ  mHph Ä sH 8hy05 hè^ >*B*	CJ  OJ PJ  QJ ^J aJ  mH$ph Ä sH$ 8hy05 hè^ >*B*	CJ  OJ PJ  QJ ^J aJ  mHph Ä sH 0hy05 hè^ >*B*	CJ  OJ PJ  QJ ^J aJ  ph Ä  -hy05 hè^ B*CJ  OJ PJ  QJ ^J aJ  ph    6j    hy05 hè^ B*CJ  OJ PJ  QJ U^J aJ  ph    !“     º æ »   Ã Œ : ; B C D E ò ô † ° ¢ £

a$gdè^                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  two others, May and August, showed job growth of more than 200,000. Only three months out of our hypothetical year, January, April and July, were particularly close to the ìtrueî level of job creation, 150,000 jobs.When traders put too much weight on data that can mislead, the stock market can soar or swoon for no good reason. Business executives may make decisions based on economic trends that donít exist. And journalists risk giving their readers or viewers a misleading view of where things stand in the American economy.Human beings, unfortunately, are bad at perceiving randomness. If you go to a baseball game and watch a commanding performance by your team, it tells you very nearly nothing about how the team will perform over the course of a season. Similarly, one month of jobs numbers doesnít tell you much of anything about how the economy is actually doing.None of this is meant to cast aspersions on the Bureau of Labor Statistics, the arm of the Labor Department that faces the unenviable task of trying to discern how many jobs there are in the United States each month. The bureau does so by conducting an enormous survey of 144,000 employers who together employ about a third of all nonagricultural workers. It is one of the most important economic data releases, in no small part because it comes out quickly; results from a survey the bureau took in the middle of last month, for example, will be released on Friday, before almost any other data about the April economy is available.Even with all those survey participants, there is sampling error; the employers responding to the survey might be different from the nationís employers as a whole. And the Labor Departmentís initial release, coming as it does so soon after the survey, is released before all the data is in, with researchers filling in the gaps with statistical estimates that might prove wrong. Only in later weeks and months is all the data available, and the bureau then revises its initial numbers.The sampling error becomes magnified because those of us following the jobs report donít focus on the total number of jobs in the economy (more than 130 million). We focus on the relatively small change in the number of these jobs from month to month (typically a few hundred thousand, at most).Whether weíre snarky newspaper journalists on Twitter or hedge-fund managers trying to trade currencies, we obsess over these reports because we have little choice but to care about how the economy is doing. Its condition affects whether our employers should expand, when we should buy a house or retire and thousands of other decisions. But itís worth remembering that no one report can neatly summarize the health of a $17 trillion economy of 300 million people, certainly not in something close to real time.At 8:30 a.m. on the first Friday of any given month, we all actually know a lot less than you might think. The closest thing to an accurate description of the economyís condition is a description that comes with a lot of humility.                            ÿD ŸD F F oG pG ÍI ÎI —K “K ˙L ˚L ˚N ¸N „O ‰O ˙            ˙            ˙            ˙            ˙            ˙            ˙            ˙            ˙            ˙            ˙            ˙            ˙            ˙            ¯                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             ( gdP9ï  2 1êh:pÈUÏ ∞–/ ∞‡=!∞†"∞†#ê†$ê†%∞  ∞–∞–ê–                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            Æ  D d                    ‡‡¸@                                 b  ≤
